-- China shares snap long-winning run, property falls
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Wed Jul 30, 2014 03:06AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, July 30 (Reuters) - China's major indexes broke a long-winning streak on Wednesday, with early gains led by index heavyweight PetroChina Co Ltd <601857.SS> offset by falls in property companies and banks.

The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> ended down 0.1 percent at 2,181.24 points, breaking its six-day winning streak which was the longest since August 2013. The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the leading Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings slipped 0.4 percent, ending eight straight days of gains. PetroChina was among top index boosts in Shanghai, climbing more than 6 percent at one point before trimming gains to end 3.1 percent higher. The government said on Tuesday it had launched a corruption investigation into former domestic security chief Zhou Yongkang, who served as CNPC's general manager from 1996-1998. [ID:nL4N0Q436P] Shares of Poly Real Estate Group Co Ltd <600048.SS> dropped 5.5 percent while China Fortune Land Co Ltd <600340.SS> fell 5 percent.